    "verdict": "two-orbit ansatz is dead at large m as well; the obstruction at m <= 12 is generic, not finite-size.",
    "key_findings": [
      "Zero survivors at every tested m in {14,15,16,18,20,25,30}.",
      "Closed-form Oa+Ia 2-eq solutions exist (94-4484 per m) but only at m in {16, 20} did any land inside the convex window (4 each), and all of them violate strict convexity.",
      "For all such convex-window candidates, the chosen 4-witness sets have witness_residual_spread ~ 0.5-0.7, meaning the 4 chosen distances are far from equal: the additional D_AB(b1)=D_AB(b2) and D_BA(b1)=D_BA(b2) constraints needed for actual 4-bad are not satisfied.",
      "A brute-force 60x31 grid scan over (r,phi) in (cos(pi/m), sec(pi/m)) x (-pi/m, pi/m) finds: every strictly-convex point has vertex multiplicity at most 2 (not even 3-bad). No (r,phi) is even close to all-vertex 4-bad.",
      "The Ob+Ia and Oa+Ib combinations yield essentially no convex-window candidates; the Ob+Ib combination forces phi to discrete values (mostly phi=0) leaving r unconstrained, but no r in the convex window gives global 4-bad.",
      "Same structural failure as m <= 12: in the convex window, the inner-orbit constraint forces r_b too close to 1; outside the convex window solutions exist but are concave."
